<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<chapter xml:id="ch2-First-Order" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>First-Order Differential Equations</title>

    <introduction>
        <p>
            In this chapter, we shall study first-order ordinary differential
            equations that can be written in standard form
            <md xml:id="eq-First-order-general" number="yes">
                y'=f(x,y).
            </md>
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- Section - Introduction to First-Order Differential Equations -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <section xml:id="sec-Intro-to-first-order">
        <title>Introduction to First-Order Differential Equations</title>

        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- Subsection - Particular, General, and Singular Solutions -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <subsection xml:id="subsec-Part-general-singular">
            <title>Particular, General, and Singular Solutions</title>

            <definition xml:id="def-Particular-general-singular">
                <title>Particular, General, and Singular Solutions</title>

                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A function <m>y=y(x)</m> is said to be a
                        <term>solution</term> of differential equation
                        <xref ref="eq-First-order-general"/> on an interval
                        <m>I</m> provided it is differentiable on <m>I</m> and
                        <md>
                            y'(x)=f\left(x,y(x)\right)\text{ for all }x\in I
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        A one-parameter family of solutions <m>y=y(x,c)</m> of
                        differential equation
                        <xref ref="eq-First-order-general"/> containing an
                        arbitrary constant <m>c</m> is called a
                        <term>general solution</term>.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Any particular choice of a specific value for <m>c</m>
                        yields a <term>particular solution</term>.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        A first-order differential equation may have both a
                        general solution involving an arbitrary constant
                        <m>c</m> and particular solutions that cannot be
                        obtained from it by any choice of <m>c</m>.
                        Such exceptional solutions are called
                        <term>singular solutions</term> (see Examples
                        <xref ref="example-Singular"/> in Section
                        <xref ref="sec-Separable"/> ).
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        To solve <xref ref="eq-First-order-general"/> is to find
                        <em>all</em> of its solutions.
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </definition>

            <note>
                <p>
                    Since a differentiable function is necessarily continuous,
                    every solution <m>y=y(x)</m> of
                    <xref ref="eq-First-order-general"/> on an interval <m>I</m>
                    must be continuous on <m>I</m>.
                </p>
            </note>

            <p>
                For a first-order equation of the form
                <md>
                    y'=f(x),
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                where <m>f(x)</m> is a continuous function on an interval
                <m>I</m>, a <term>general solution</term> on <m>I</m> is
                <md>
                    y=\int f(x)\,dx=F(x)+c\qquad (c\in \mathbb{R}),
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                where <m>F(x)</m> is an antiderivative of <m>f</m> on <m>I</m>.
                By the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus (see, e.g.,
                <xref ref="Stewart"/> ), we can set
                <md>
                    F(x):=\int_{x_0}^{x}f(t)\,dt,\quad x\in I,
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                where <m>x_{0}</m> is a fixed point in <m>I</m>.
            </p>

            <example>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The one-parameter family <m>y=c</m> (
                                <m>c\in \mathbb{R}</m> ) is a general solution
                                of the equation.
                                <md>
                                    y'=0
                                </md>
                            </p>

                            <p>
                                on <m>(-\infty,\infty)</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The one-parameter family <m>y=\ln|x|+c</m> (
                                <m>c \in \mathbb{R}</m> ) is the general
                                solution of the equation.
                                <md>
                                    y'=\dfrac{1}{x}
                                </md>
                            </p>

                            <p>
                                on each of the intervals <m>(-\infty,0)</m> and
                                <m>(0,\infty)</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </example>
        </subsection>
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- Subsection - Particular, General, and Singular Solutions -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <subsection xml:id="subsec-IVP">
            <title>Initial Value Problems</title>

            <definition xml:id="def-Initial-value-problem">
                <title>Initial Value Problem</title>

                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A first-order differential equation
                        <xref ref="eq-First-order-general"/> is often
                        accompanied by a condition of the form:
                        <md>
                            y(x_{0})=y_{0},
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        where <m>x_{0}</m> and <m>y_{0}</m> are specified
                        values.
                        Such a condition is called an
                        <term>initial condition</term> (IC) and such a problem
                        <md xml:id="eq-IVP" number="yes">
                            y'=f(x,y),\ y(x_{0})=y_{0}
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        is called an <term>initial value problem</term> (IVP).
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        A solution of the initial value problem
                        <xref ref="eq-IVP"/> is a function <m>y=y(x)</m>
                        satisfying both the differential equation on some
                        interval <m>I</m> containing <m>x_{0}</m> and the
                        initial condition.
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </definition>

            <p>
                One way to solve initial value problem <xref ref="eq-IVP"/> is
                to
            </p>

            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            first find the general solution <m>y=y(x,c)</m> of
                            the equation, which, provided the differential
                            equation is of the form
                            <md>
                                y'=f(x),
                            </md>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            can be done via indefinite integration
                            <md>
                                y=\int f(x)\,dx,
                            </md>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            and
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            then, plug <m>x = x_{0}</m> and <m>y = y_{0}</m>
                            into the general solution, and solve for <m>c</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>

            <example xml:id="example-IVP-reciprocal">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Solve the initial value problem
                        <md>
                            y'=\dfrac{1}{x},\ y(1)=0.
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <em>Solution:</em> Considering that the initial
                        <m>x</m>-value 1 is in the interval <m>(0,\infty)</m>,
                        where <m>|x|=x</m>, we obtain the unique solution of the
                        IVP from the general solution <m>y=\ln|x|+c=\ln x+c</m>
                        of the equation on <m>(0,\infty)</m> by substituting the
                        values <m>x=1</m> and <m>y=0</m> into it:
                        <md>
                            0=\ln 1+c,
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        which yields <m>c = 0</m>.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Thus, the unique solution to the IVP on
                        <m>(0,\infty)</m> is
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <md>
                            \boxed{y=\ln x.}
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </example>

            <p>
                An alternative <term>definite-integral approach</term> to
                solving an initial value problem of the form
                <md xml:id="eq-IVP-single-variable" number="yes">
                    y'=f(x),\ y(x_{0})=y_{0},
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                which bypasses finding the general solution of the differential
                equation, is based on the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus and,
                provided the function <m>f(x)</m> is continuous on an interval
                <m>I</m> containing <m>x_{0}</m>, gives the <em>unique</em>
                solution of the IVP by the formula
                <md>
                    y=y_{0}+\int_{x_0}^{x}f(t)\,dt.
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                In the following two examples, we will compare the two
                approaches to solving initial value problem
                <xref ref="eq-IVP-single-variable"/>.
            </p>

            <example>
                <title>Indefinite Integral Approach</title>

                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Solve the differential equation
                        <md>
                            y'=x\sqrt{x^{2}+9},\ y(-4)=0
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        First, we find the general solution of the equation
                        <md>
                            y= \int x \sqrt{x^{2} + 9}\, dx
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Using substitution ( <m>u = x^{2} + 9</m>, so
                        <m>du = 2x \, dx</m> ), we obtain
                        <md>
                            y= \frac{1}{3}(x^{2} + 9)^{\frac{3}{2}}+ C
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Next, we need to determine the value of <m>c</m> for
                        which the solution we have obtained will satisfy the
                        IVP.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Substituting in the initial condition gives
                        <md>
                            \dfrac{1}{3}\left((-4)^{2}+9\right)^{3/2}+c=0,
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        which we solve to find <m>c=-\dfrac{125}{3}</m>.
                        The unique solution is, therefore,
                        <md>
                            \boxed{y = \dfrac{1}{3}(x^2+9)^{3/2}-\dfrac{125}{3},}
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        or
                        <md>
                            \boxed{y = \dfrac{1}{3}\left((x^2+9)^{3/2}-125\right).}
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </example>

            <example>
                <title>Definite Integral Approach</title>

                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Solve the differential equation
                        <md>
                            y'=xe^{-x},\ y(0)=1.
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        The desired solution is given by the formula
                        <md>
                            y=1+\int_{0}^{x}te^{-t}\,dt.
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Integrating by parts, with
                        <md>
                            <mrow>u\amp =t,\amp du\amp =dt</mrow>
                            <mrow>dv\amp =e^{-t}\;dt,\amp v\amp =-e^{-t},</mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        we have:
                        <md>
                            <mrow>\int_{0}^{x}te^{-t}\,dt\amp = \left[\left.-te^{-t}\right|_{0}^{x}+\int_{0}^{x} e^{-t}\,dt\right]</mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp =\left[\left.-xe^{-x}-e^{-t}\right|_{0}^{x}\right] </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp =\left[-xe^{-x}-(e^{-x}-1)\right]</mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp =-xe^{-x}-e^{-x}+1=-(x+1)e^{-x}+1.</mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Therefore, the solution is
                        <md>
                            \boxed{y(x)=-(x+1)e^{-x}+2.}
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </example>
        </subsection>
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- Subsection - Exercises for Intro to First-Order Differential Equations -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <subsection>
            <title>Exercises for <xref ref="sec-Intro-to-first-order"/></title>

            <p>
                Find a general solution of the following equations.
            </p>

            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle y' = xe^{-x^2}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}= 3x^{2}\sin(x^{3})</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\dfrac{dy}{dt}= 4e^{t} \cos(t)</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>

            <p>
                Solve the following initial value problems.
            </p>

            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle y' = \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{x+2}}, \ y(2)=-1</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle y' = (t^{2} + 2t + 1)e^{t}, \ y(0) = 2</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}= \dfrac{\ln(x)}{x}, \ y(1) = 0 \quad (x &gt; 0)</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </subsection>
    </section>
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- Section - Separable Differential Equations -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <section xml:id="sec-Separable">
        <title>Separable Differential Equations</title>

        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- Subsection - Motivating Example: Home Loan -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <subsection xml:id="motivation-Home-loan">
            <title>Motivating Example: Home Loan</title>

            <p>
                Suppose you want to take out a 30-year loan to purchase a house.
                If interest rates are 4.75% and you know that you can afford at
                most $1,250 per month, you would like to determine the most
                expensive house that you can purchase in order pay off the loan
                on time.
                To do this, define <m>L(t)</m> as the amount that you owe after
                <m>t</m> years.
                Since you can afford $1,250 per month, your annual payments will
                be <m>\$1,250 \times 12 = \$15,000</m>.
                The balance due will gain 4.75% interest, so that amount added
                to the balance annually is <m>0.0475L</m>.
                Thus, the rate of change in the amount of money due is given by
                the difference between the amount the loan increases and the
                amount that you pay on the loan, or
                <m>\dfrac{dL}{dt}=0475L - 15000</m>.
                The initial condition is <m>L(30) = 0</m>, because you want the
                entire loan to be paid off by the end of the 30 years.
                This gives the initial value problem
                <md xml:id="eq-Home-loan" number="yes">
                    \frac{dL}{dt}= 0.0475L - 15000, \, L(30) = 0.
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                This is a separable equation, as we will see momentarily (also a
                linear equation, as we will see in Section
                <xref ref="sec-Linear"/> ).
                The solution to <xref ref="eq-Home-loan"/> is
                <md>
                    L(t) = \frac{6000000}{19}\left(1 - e^{\frac{19}{400}t-\frac{57}{40}}\right).
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                The size of the loan you should take is the amount you owe at
                the beginning, or <m>L(0)</m>, which is $239,839.43.
            </p>
        </subsection>
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- Subsection - Separable Differential Equations -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <subsection>
            <title>Definition and Examples</title>

            <definition xml:id="def-Separable">
                <title>Separable Differential Equation</title>

                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A first-order differential equation
                        <md>
                            \dfrac{dy}{dx}=f(x,y),
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        whose right-hand side can be factored into
                        <m>g(x)h(y)</m>, i.e., it can written in the form
                        <md xml:id="eq-Seperable-form" number="yes">
                            \dfrac{dy}{dx}=g(x)h(y),
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        is called <term>separable</term>.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        There are two special cases of separable equations:
                        <md>
                            <mrow> \frac{dy}{dx}\amp =g(x) \quad (h(y)=1),</mrow>
                            <mrow> \frac{dy}{dx}\amp =h(y)\quad (g(x)=1) \qquad \text{(called an \emph{autonomous equation})}.</mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </definition>

            <example>
                <p>
                    <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}=x^{2}e^{-y}</m> is separable.
                </p>
            </example>

            <example>
                <p>
                    <m>\dfrac{dy}{dt}=\sin t^{2}</m> is separable.
                </p>
            </example>

            <example>
                <p>
                    The <term>exponential</term> differential equation
                    <m>\dfrac{dx}{dt}=kx</m> where <m>k\in \mathbb{R}</m> is
                    separable (and autonomous).
                </p>
            </example>

            <example>
                <p>
                    The <term>logistic</term> differential equation
                    <m>\dfrac{dy}{dt}=ky\left(1-\dfrac{y}{N}\right)</m> where (
                    <m>k, N &gt; 0 </m> are constants) is separable (and
                    autonomous).
                </p>
            </example>

            <example>
                <p>
                    <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}=\dfrac{\sqrt{y}}{xy+x+y+1}</m> is
                    separable.
                </p>
            </example>

            <example>
                <p>
                    <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}=y+x</m> is not separable.
                    As we will see in Section <xref ref="sec-Linear"/>, this
                    equation is also <term>linear</term>.
                </p>
            </example>

            <example>
                <p>
                    <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}=y^{3}+xy+5</m> is not separable.
                </p>
            </example>
        </subsection>
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- Subsection - Method of Separation of Variables -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <subsection xml:id="subsec-Separation-of-variables">
            <title>Method of Separation of Variables</title>

            <p>
                Consider a separable differential equation
                <md>
                    \dfrac{dy}{dx}=g(x)h(y).
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                Observe that, if there is such a <m>c\in \mathbb{R}</m> such
                that <m>h(c)=0</m>, then the constant function <m>y=c</m> is a
                so-called <term>equilibrium solution</term> of the equation.
                The method of separation of variables is used for solving these
                differential equations.
            </p>
            <!-- ===================================================== -->
            <!-- ===================================================== -->
            <!-- Subsubsection - How Separation Works -->
            <!-- ===================================================== -->
            <!-- ===================================================== -->
            <paragraphs xml:id="subsubsec-How-separation-works">
                <title>How Separation of Variables Works</title>

                <p>
                    The method of separation of variables works as follows:
                </p>

                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Find all equilibrium solutions from the equation
                                <md>
                                    h(y)=0.
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Separate the variables:
                                <md>
                                    \frac{1}{h(y)}\, dy=g(x)\,dx.
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Integrate both sides:
                                <md>
                                    \int\frac{1}{h(y)}\,dy=\int g(x)\,dx.
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Solve the resulting equation for <m>y</m>,
                                whenever possible, obtaining a general solution.
                                The equilibrium solutions that are not included
                                in this general solution give the singular
                                solutions.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>

                <example xml:id="example-Singular">
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            The separable differential equation
                            <md>
                                y'=y^{2}.
                            </md>
                            has a general solution of <m>y=\dfrac{1}{c-x}</m> (
                            <m>c\in\mathbb{R}</m> ) and the singular equilibrium
                            solution <m>y=0</m> not included in the general
                            solution.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                </example>

                <remark>
                    <p>
                        If it is impossible (or impractical) to solve the
                        resulting equation for <m>y</m>, the general solution is
                        said to be an <term>implicit general solution</term>.
                    </p>
                </remark>

                <example xml:id="example-Separable-worked-out">
                    <title>Solving a Separable Differential Equation</title>

                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Solve the differential equation
                            <md>
                                \frac{dy}{dt}=\frac{2y+1}{t}.
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </statement>

                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            To solve this separable DE, we apply the method of
                            separation of variables.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Find the equilibrium solutions from the
                                        equation
                                        <md>
                                            2y+1=0.
                                        </md>
                                    </p>

                                    <p>
                                        Clearly, there is only one:
                                        <m>y=-\dfrac{1}{2}</m>.
                                    </p>
                                </li>

                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Separate the variables:
                                        <md>
                                            \frac{1}{2y+1}dy=\frac{1}{t}dt\quad (y\neq -1/2)
                                        </md>
                                    </p>
                                </li>

                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Integrate both sides:
                                        <md>
                                            <mrow> \int\frac{1}{2y+1}dy\amp =\int\frac{1}{t}dt,</mrow>
                                            <mrow> \frac{1}{2}\ln|2y+1|\amp =\ln|t|+c\ (c\in \mathbb{R}).</mrow>
                                        </md>
                                    </p>
                                </li>

                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Solve the resulting equation for
                                        <m>y</m>:
                                        <md>
                                            <mrow> \ln|2y+1|\amp =2\ln|t|+c\amp \amp(\text{where } c\in \mathbb{R}) </mrow>
                                            <mrow> |2y+1|\amp =e^{2\ln|t|+c} \amp \amp\text{(exponentiate both sides)}</mrow>
                                            <mrow> |2y+1|\amp =e^{c}\;t^{2} \amp \amp\text{(exponent rules)}</mrow>
                                            <mrow> |2y+1|\amp =c_{1}\;t^{2} \amp \amp(\text{replace } c_{1}:=e^{c} &gt; 0)</mrow>
                                            <mrow> 2y+1\amp =\pm c_{1}\;t^{2}</mrow>
                                            <mrow> 2y+1\amp =c_{2}t^{2} \amp \amp(\text{ where }c_{2} := \pm c_{1} \neq 0 ) </mrow>
                                            <mrow> y\amp =c_{2}\;t^{2}-\frac{1}{2} \amp \amp(\text{solve for }y)</mrow>
                                        </md>
                                    </p>

                                    <p>
                                        Renaming <m>c_{2}</m> to simply
                                        <m>c</m>, we obtain the general solution
                                        <md>
                                            \boxed{y(x)=ct^2-\dfrac{1}{2}\qquad\text{where } c\in \mathbb{R}\text{ and }t\neq 0}
                                        </md>
                                    </p>

                                    <p>
                                        <em>Question:</em> What is the reason
                                        for the requirement that <m>t\neq 0</m>?
                                    </p>

                                    <p>
                                        Observe that the equilibrium solution
                                        <m>y=-\dfrac{1}{2}</m> is attained when
                                        <m>c=0</m>.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </example>
            </paragraphs>
            <!-- ===================================================== -->
            <!-- ===================================================== -->
            <!-- Subsubsection - Why Separation of Variables Works -->
            <!-- ===================================================== -->
            <!-- ===================================================== -->
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Why Separation of Variables Works</title>

                <p>
                    The method of separation of variables is based on the
                    substitution rule for indefinite integrals
                    <xref ref="Stewart"/>.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Indeed, let <m>y=y(x)</m> be a nonequilibrium solution of a
                    separable equation
                    <md xml:id="eq-SDE" number="yes">
                        \dfrac{dy}{dx}=g(x)h(y)
                    </md>
                    on an interval <m>I</m>.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Then, for all <m>x\in I</m>,
                    <md xml:id="eq-Why-separation-works" number="yes">
                        y'(x)=g(x)h(y(x)).
                    </md>
                </p>

                <p>
                    Dividing both sides of differential equation
                    <xref ref="eq-Why-separation-works"/> by <m>h(y(x))</m> and
                    integrating, we obtain
                    <md>
                        \int\frac{1}{h(y(x))}y'(x)\,dx=\int g(x)\,dx \text{ on }I.
                    </md>
                </p>

                <p>
                    Using the substitution <m>y=y(x)</m>, we obtain
                    <md xml:id="eq-INTE" number="yes">
                        \int\frac{1}{h(y)}\,dy=\int g(x)\, dx.
                    </md>
                </p>

                <p>
                    Thus, any nonequilibrium solution <m>y(x)</m> of
                    differential equation <xref ref="eq-SDE"/> satisfies
                    integral equation <xref ref="eq-INTE"/>.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Conversely, a function <m>y=y(x)</m>, implicitly defined by
                    integral equation <xref ref="eq-INTE"/> on the interval
                    <m>I</m>, solves <xref ref="eq-SDE"/> on <m>I</m>.
                    Indeed, differentiating <xref ref="eq-INTE"/> relative to
                    <m>x</m> by the chain rule (considering <m>y=y(x)</m> ), we
                    arrive at <xref ref="eq-Why-separation-works"/> for all
                    <m>x\in I</m>.
                </p>
            </paragraphs>
        </subsection>
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- Subsection - Separable Exercises -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <subsection>
            <title>Exercises for Section <xref ref="sec-Separable"/></title>

            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Determine which of the following first order
                            differential equations are separable.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}= 3x^{2}y</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>

                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\displaystyle y' = e^{2x+y}</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>

                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}= x^{2} + 2xy + y^{2}</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>

                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\displaystyle \tan(x) y' = y^{2} + 1</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>

                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}= xy + x + y</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Apply the method of separation of variables to
                            verify <xref ref="example-Singular"/>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>

            <p>
                Find a general solution for each of the following equations.
            </p>

            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle (x^{2} + 1)y' = y^{2} + 1</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle y' = 3x^{2}y^{2}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle \left(\frac{2y}{x}\right) \frac{dy}{dx}= 0 \quad (x \ne 0)</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle \sin(y) y' = \cos(x)</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle y' = 3x^{2}e^{y}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>

            <p>
                Solve the following initial value problems.
            </p>

            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle y\frac{dy}{dx}= x^{2} + 1, \ y(0) = -2</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}= \frac{y}{x}, \ y(1) = 1</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle x^{2} y' = y, \ y(1) = 0</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}= xy + x + y + 1, \ y(0) = 0</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle x\dfrac{dy}{dx}-y = 2x^{2}y, \ y(1) = 1</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle y' = 2x(y^{2} + 1), \ y(\sqrt{\pi}) = 0</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle xy' = 2y\ln(x), \ y(1) = 2</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </subsection>
    </section>
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- Section - Applications of Separable Equations -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <section xml:id="sepapp">
        <title>Applications of Separable Equations</title>

        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- Subsection - Radiocarbon Dating -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <subsection>
            <title>Radiocarbon Dating</title>

            <p>
                Carbon-14 is a radioactive isotope of carbon produced in the
                upper atmosphere by radiation from the sun.
                Plants absorb carbon dioxide from the air, and living organisms
                eat plants.
                The ratio of normal carbon (Carbon-12) to Carbon-14 in the air
                and living things is nearly constant.
                When a living creature dies, the Carbon-14 begins to decrease
                due to radioactive decay.
                By comparing the amounts of Carbon-12 and Carbon-14, the amount
                of Carbon-14 that has decayed can be determined.
            </p>
            <!-- ===================================================== -->
            <!-- ===================================================== -->
            <!-- Subsubsubsection - Mathematical Model -->
            <!-- ===================================================== -->
            <!-- ===================================================== -->
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Mathematical Model</title>

                <p>
                    Let <m>y(t) =</m> amount of Carbon-14 present at time
                    <m>t</m> after death.
                </p>

                <p>
                    The model of radioactive decay we'll use is:
                    <md>
                        y' = -ky\quad\text{where}\quad k&gt;0.
                    </md>
                </p>

                <p>
                    We need additional information to find <m>k</m>.
                    For example, if we have the half-life of Carbon-14 (which is
                    standard information for a radioactive isotope), we can
                    determine <m>k</m>.
                </p>
            </paragraphs>

            <paragraphs>
                <title>Sample Case</title>

                <p>
                    The half-life of Carbon-14 is approximately 5,730 years.
                    Suppose remains have been found in which it is estimated
                    that 30% of the original Carbon-14 is present.
                    Estimate the age of the remains.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <em>Step 1:</em> Solve the IVP
                    <md>
                        y'=-ky, \ y(0)=y_{0}.
                    </md>
                </p>

                <p>
                    <em>Note:</em> We can also set <m>y(0) = 100</m> (for 100%)
                    or <m>y(0) = 1</m> (for 100% in decimal form).
                </p>

                <p>
                    By separation of variables, we see that the general solution
                    is
                    <md>
                        y(t) = ce^{-kt}.
                    </md>
                </p>

                <p>
                    Using the initial condition, <m>c = y_{0}</m>, so
                    <md>
                        y(t) = y_{0}e^{-kt}.
                    </md>
                </p>

                <p>
                    <em>Step 2:</em> Find <m>k</m>
                </p>

                <p>
                    To find <m>k</m>, we will use the half-life of Carbon-14.
                    Since the half-life is the amount of time for half of the
                    sample to decay, we know that
                    <m>y(5730)=\frac{1}{2}y_{0}.</m> Therefore,
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \frac{1}{2}y_{0}\amp = y_{0} e^{-k(5730)} </mrow>
                        <mrow> \ln \frac{1}{2}\amp = -5730k </mrow>
                        <mrow> k\amp = -\frac{\ln\frac{1}{2}}{5730}\approx 0.000121. </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>

                <p>
                    <em>Step 3:</em> Determine the age of the remains.
                </p>

                <p>
                    At time <m>t_{\ast}</m> (the age), we have 30%of the
                    original amount of Carbon-14, or
                    <m>y(t_{\ast}) = 0.3y_{0}.</m> So, plugging this into our
                    solution for <m>y(t)</m> will allow us to solve for the age
                    of the remains.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>0.3y_{0}\amp = y_{0} e^{-0.000121t_{\ast}} </mrow>
                        <mrow>\ln 0.3\amp = -0.000121 t_{\ast}</mrow>
                        <mrow> t_{\ast}\amp = -\frac{\ln 0.3}{0.000121}\approx 9,950 \text{ years}. </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </paragraphs>
        </subsection>
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- Subsection - Geometric Example -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <subsection>
            <title>Geometric Example</title>

            <p>
                Find the curve with slope <m>\displaystyle -\frac{x}{y}</m>
                through the point (0, 1).
            </p>

            <p>
                <em>Solution:</em> The differential equation
                <md>
                    \frac{dy}{dx}= -\frac{x}{y}
                </md>
                modeling this problem has the implicit general solution
                <md>
                    x^{2} + y^{2} = c.
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                Substituting <m>x=0</m> and <m>y=1</m> into it, we arrive at
                <md>
                    1^{2} + 0^{2}=c,
                </md>
                so <m>c=1</m>, and therefore, the desired curve is the unit
                circle
                <md>
                    x^{2} + y^{2} = 1
                </md>.
            </p>
        </subsection>
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- Subsubsubsection - Mixing Problem -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <subsection>
            <title>Mixing Problem</title>

            <p>
                A typical mixing problem is about the amount or concentration of
                a <em>solute</em> in a <em>solution</em> with certain flows of
                solutions with the same solute into and out of a container
                holding the solution.
            </p>

            <p>
                <em>Model:</em> Let <m>y(t)</m> be the amount of solute in the
                container at any time <m>t</m>.
                Then, we have that
            </p>

            <blockquote>
                <p>
                    rate of change in amount of solute = total solute inflow
                    rate <m>-</m> total solute outlow rate
                </p>

                <p>
                    (i.e., <m>y' = \mbox{rate in}- \mbox{rate out}</m> ).
                </p>
            </blockquote>

            <p>
                <em>Note:</em> The total solute inflow rate is determined by
                summing the inflow rates from each source, and similarly for the
                total solute outflow rate.
            </p>

            <p>
                Each solute inflow rate is found by multiplying the rate at
                which fluid flows into the container by the concentration of
                solute:
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    \text{inflow rate}= \text{(rate of fluid inflow)}\cdot \text{(concentration of solute)}.
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                Each solute outflow rate is found by multiplying the rate at
                which fluid flows out of the container by the concentration of
                solute in the container:
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    \text{outflow rate}=\left(\text{rate of fluid outflow}\right) \cdot \left(\frac{\text{amount of solute in container}}{\text{volume of solution in container}}\right).
                </md>
            </p>

            <note>
                <p>
                    The resulting DE is a first-order linear equation regardless
                    of whether the rates, concentrations, and volume are
                    constant or variable.
                    When all of the rates, concentrations, and volume are
                    constant, this equation is also separable (and even
                    autonomous).
                </p>
            </note>

            <example>
                <title>Mixing Problem with Constant Volume</title>

                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A tank contains <m>1000</m> L of pure water.
                        A brine containing <m>0.05</m> kg/L of salt enters the
                        tank at a constant rate of <m>5</m> L/min.
                        A brine containing <m>0.04</m> kg/L of salt enters the
                        tank at a constant rate of <m>10</m> L/min.
                        The solution is kept thoroughly mixed and drains from
                        the tank at a constant rate of <m>15</m> L/min.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Set up an initial value problem describing
                                    how the amount of salt in the tank changes
                                    over time.
                                </p>
                            </li>

                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Find the amount of salt in the tank after
                                    <m>t</m> min.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>

                    <figure xml:id="fig-mix1">
                        <caption>Mixing Problem with Constant Volume</caption>
                        <image source="mixconst1.jpg" width="60%">
                            <shortdescription>
                                Image of cylindrical tank with two input sources
                                and one output drain.
                            </shortdescription>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </statement>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Let <m>y(t)</m> be the amount of salt in the
                                    tank (kg) after <m>t</m> min.
                                </p>

                                <p>
                                    The rate of change of the amount of salt in
                                    the tank <m>\dfrac{dy}{dt}</m> (kg/min)
                                    consists of the two components:
                                </p>

                                <p>
                                    <ul>
                                        <li>
                                            <p>
                                                the inflow rate of salt entering
                                                the tank, which consists of the
                                                sum of the rates coming from the
                                                two sources
                                                <md>
                                                    <mrow> \text{rate in}\amp = 5 \, \frac{\text{L}}{\text{min}}\cdot 0.05 \, \frac{\text{kg}}{\text{L}}+ 10 \, \frac{\text{L}}{\text{min}}\cdot 0.04 \, \frac{\text{kg}}{\text{L}} </mrow>
                                                    <mrow> \amp = 0.65\ \text{ kg/min}.</mrow>
                                                </md>
                                            </p>
                                        </li>

                                        <li>
                                            <p>
                                                the outflow rate of salt leaving
                                                the tank:
                                                <md>
                                                    \text{rate out}= 15 \frac{\text{L}}{\text{min}}\cdot\dfrac{y \text{ kg}}{1000 \text{ L}}= 0.015y\ \text{ kg/min}.
                                                </md>
                                            </p>
                                        </li>
                                    </ul>
                                </p>

                                <p>
                                    Since initially there was no salt in the
                                    tank ( <m>y(0)=0</m> ), we obtain at the
                                    following IVP model for the mixing problem:
                                    <md>
                                        \dfrac{dy}{dt}=0.65-0.015y,\ y(0)=0.
                                    </md>
                                </p>
                            </li>

                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    The DE is separable, and more precisely, it
                                    is autonomous.
                                    Applying the method of separation of
                                    variables, we have:
                                </p>

                                <p>
                                    <ul>
                                        <li>
                                            <p>
                                                The equilibrium solution is
                                                <m>y=\dfrac{0.65}{0.015}</m>.
                                            </p>
                                        </li>

                                        <li>
                                            <p>
                                                Separating the variables, we
                                                obtain
                                                <md>
                                                    <mrow> \dfrac{1}{0.65-0.015y}\,dy\amp = 1\,dt </mrow>
                                                    <mrow> \int\dfrac{1}{0.65-0.015y}\,dy\amp =\int 1\,dt </mrow>
                                                    <mrow> \dfrac{1}{-0.015}\ln|0.65-0.015y|\amp = t+c_{1} \quad (c_{1} \in \R). </mrow>
                                                </md>
                                            </p>

                                            <p>
                                                Now we solve for <m>y</m>:
                                                <md>
                                                    <mrow> \ln|0.015y-0.65|\amp = -0.015t+c \quad (c \in \R) </mrow>
                                                    <mrow> y(t)\amp = \frac{0.65}{0.015}+ce^{-0.015t}\quad (c \in \R) </mrow>
                                                </md>
                                            </p>
                                        </li>

                                        <li>
                                            <p>
                                                Find <m>c</m>: Using the initial
                                                condition <m>y(0)=0</m>, we have
                                                <md>
                                                    0 = \frac{0.65}{0.015}+ c,
                                                </md>
                                                so <m>c=-\dfrac{0.65}{0.015}</m>
                                                and the solution of the problem
                                                is
                                                <md>
                                                    \boxed{y(t) =\frac{0.65}{0.015}-\frac{0.65}{0.015}e^{-0.015t}.}
                                                </md>
                                                Note that <m>y</m> increasingly
                                                tends to the equilibrium
                                                <m> \dfrac{0.65}{0.015}\approx 43 </m>
                                                kg as <m> t\to \infty </m>, but
                                                never attains it.
                                            </p>
                                        </li>
                                    </ul>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>

                    <figure xml:id="fig-mix2">
                        <caption>
                            The Graph of <m>y</m> ( <m>y(0)=0</m> )
                        </caption>

                        <image source="mixconst2.jpg" width="80%">
                            <description>
                                <p>
                                    Curve that starts at origin and increases
                                    towards a horizontal asymptote at
                                    <m>y=43</m>.
                                </p>
                            </description>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </solution>
            </example>
        </subsection>
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- Subsection - Newton's Law of Cooling/Heating -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <subsection>
            <title>Newton's Law of Cooling/Heating</title>

            <p>
                Newton's Law of Cooling/Heating states that the rate of change
                of the temperature of an object, <m>T</m>, is proportional to
                the difference between the ambient temperature of the
                surroundings, <m>A</m>, and <m>T</m>:
                <md xml:id="eq-cool" number="yes">
                    \dfrac{dT}{dt}= k(A - T),
                </md>
                where <m>k &gt; 0</m> is the constant of proportionality.
            </p>

            <example xml:id="ex-newt">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Consider a tray of cookies removed from the oven at 350
                        <m>^{\circ}</m> F and placed in a room with a
                        temperature of 72 <m>^{\circ}</m> F.
                        If the cookies are at 240 <m>^{\circ}</m> F after 10
                        minutes, how long will it take for them to cool to 80
                        <m>^{\circ}</m> F?
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        The IVP modeling this situation is given by applying
                        equation <xref ref="eq-cool"/>:
                        <md>
                            \dfrac{dT}{dt}= k(72 - T), \ T(0) = 350.
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        We will apply the method of separation of variables.
                        Separating variables gives
                        <md>
                            \dfrac{1}{72-T}\, dT = k \, dt.
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Integrate both sides and solve for <m>T</m>:
                        <md>
                            <mrow> \int \dfrac{1}{72-T}\, dT\amp = \int k \, dt </mrow>
                            <mrow> -\ln|72 - T|\amp = kt + c </mrow>
                            <mrow> \ln|72 - T|\amp = -kt + c </mrow>
                            <mrow> 72 - T\amp = ce^{-kt} </mrow>
                            <mrow> T\amp = 72 + ce^{-kt}. </mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        We next need to determine <m>c</m> and <m>k</m>.
                        We first find <m>c</m> using the initial condition:
                        <md>
                            350 = T(0) = 72 + c, \text{ so }c = 278.
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        So, we have
                        <md>
                            T = 72 + 278e^{-kt}.
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Now we use the fact (given in the problem) that
                        <m>T(10) = 240</m> to find <m>k</m>.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <md>
                            <mrow> 240 \amp = 72 + 278e^{-10k} </mrow>
                            <mrow> 168 \amp = 278 e^{-10k} </mrow>
                            <mrow> e^{-10k} \amp = \dfrac{168}{278}= \dfrac{84}{139}. </mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Then take the natural log of both sides and solve for
                        <m>k</m>:
                        <md>
                            <mrow> -10k\amp = \ln\left( \dfrac{84}{139}\right) </mrow>
                            <mrow> k\amp = -\frac{1}{10}\ln\left( \dfrac{84}{139}\right) \approx 0.053657. </mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Let <m>t_{s}</m> denote the time at which the
                        temperature of the cookies is 80 <m>^{\circ}</m> F.
                        Then
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <md>
                            80 = 72 + 278e^{-0.053657 t_s}.
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Solving for <m>t_{s}</m> gives us <m>t_{s} = 70.45</m>.
                        So, the cookies will be at 80 <m>^{\circ}</m> F after
                        70.45 minutes, or after 1 hour, 10 minutes, and 27
                        seconds.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </example>
        </subsection>
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- Subsection - Exercises for Applications of Separable Equations -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <subsection>
            <title>Exercises for Section <xref ref="sepapp"/></title>

            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Verify the solution to the Geometric Application
                            problem.
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the equation of the curve with slope
                            <m>\dfrac{x}{y}</m> through the point <m>(0, 2)</m>.
                            What type of curve is this?
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the equation of the curve with slope
                            <m>\dfrac{y}{x}</m> through the point <m>(1, 0)</m>.
                            What type of curve is this?
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            (Drug Elimination) The amount <m>y(t)</m> of a
                            certain drug in the bloodstream as a function of
                            time <m>t</m> declining at a rate proportional to
                            the current excess amount relative to the natural
                            level of the drug (typically 0) is modeled by the
                            differential equation
                            <md>
                                \frac{dy}{dt}= -r y,
                            </md>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            where <m>r &gt; 0</m>.
                            Suppose that after 2 hours, half of the initial
                            amount of the drug is left in the patient's system
                            (i.e., <m>y(2) = 0.5y(0)</m> ).
                            Find <m>y(t)</m> assuming that initially, the
                            patient is given 250 mg of the drug (i.e.,
                            <m>y(0) = 250</m> ).
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            (Radiocarbon Dating) The half-life of Carbon-14 is
                            approximately 5,730 years.
                            Suppose remains have been found in which it is
                            estimated that 65%of the original Carbon-14 has
                            decayed.
                            Estimate the age of the remains.
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            (Population Model) A new species of animal has just
                            been discovered.
                            The rate of change in the size of its population was
                            found to be proportional to the square root of its
                            current size.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Formulate a mathematical model
                                        describing the population size
                                        <m>P(t)</m> of this new species over
                                        time.
                                    </p>
                                </li>

                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        If the initial population is <m>100</m>
                                        animals and, after 2 months, the
                                        population has grown to 400 animals,
                                        determine the size of the population at
                                        any time <m>t</m>.
                                    </p>
                                </li>

                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        How long before the population has grown
                                        to 1000 animals?
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            (Logistic Population Model) A population model that
                            takes into account the fact that, as a population
                            grows in size its rate of change decreases, is the
                            <em>logistic model</em>.
                            Given a population of size <m>P(t)</m>, the logistic
                            model is defined by
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            <md>
                                \dfrac{dP}{dt}= rP\left(1 - \dfrac{P}{K}\right),
                            </md>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            where <m>r</m> is the intrinsic growth rate of the
                            population in a given area (the growth rate in the
                            absence of any restrictions) and <m>K</m> is the
                            carrying capacity of the area (the maximum
                            population that can be supported).
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            If <m>r = 2</m> per year and <m>K = 10000</m>, use
                            the logistic equation to determine the population
                            size at any time of a species with an initial
                            population of 1000.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            <em>Hint: You will need to use partial fractions to evaluate the integral on the left-hand side.</em>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </subsection>
    </section>
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- Section - Applications of Separable Equations -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <section xml:id="linear">
        <title>Linear Differential Equations and Applications</title>

        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- Subsection - Motivating Example: Evaporating Raindrop -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <subsection>
            <title>
                Motivating Example: Evaporating Raindrop <xref ref="Zill"/>
            </title>

            <p>
                As a raindrop falls, it evaporates to some extent.
                We assume that as it evaporates, it still maintains its
                spherical shape.
                We make the following additional assumptions:
            </p>

            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            the evaporation rate of the raindrop is proportional
                            to its surface area; and
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            air resistance does not impact the velocity of the
                            raindrop.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>

            <p>
                With these assumptions, the velocity <m>v(t)</m> of the raindrop
                satisfies the model
                <md>
                    \dfrac{dv}{dt}- \left(\dfrac{3\left(\frac{k}{\rho}\right)}{r_0 - \left(\frac{k}{\rho}\right)t}\right)v = g, \ v(0) = v_{0}
                </md>
                where <m>g</m> is the acceleration due to gravity, <m>\rho</m>
                is the density of the raindrop, <m>r_{0}</m> is the initial
                radius of the drop, and <m>k&gt;0</m> is the constant of
                proportionality.
                We take the downward direction to be positive.
            </p>

            <p>
                This equation is a <term>linear differential equation</term>.
                If we assume that
            </p>

            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            the initial radius of the drop is <m>1</m> cm,
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\rho = 1 \text{ kg/}\text{m}^{3}</m> (or
                            <m>\rho = 0.001 \text{ g/}\text{cm}^{3}</m> ), and
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>v_{0} = 0</m>,
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>

            <p>
                then we have
                <md>
                    v = \dfrac{73500kt^2-49t}{1500000kt-500}\text{ cm/s}.
                </md>
            </p>
        </subsection>
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- Subsection - Definition and Examples -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <subsection>
            <title>Definition and Examples</title>

            <definition>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Linear Differential Equationf-olde
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        A first-order differential equation of the form
                        <md>
                            y'+p(x)y=q(x)
                        </md>
                        with the coefficient function <m>p(x)</m> and the
                        right-hand-side function <m>q(x)</m>, both continuous on
                        an open interval <m>I</m>, is called a
                        <term>linear</term> first-order differential equation.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        If <m>q(x)\equiv 0</m> on <m>I</m>, the differential
                        equation is called <term>homogeneous</term> and
                        <term>nonhomogeneous</term> otherwise.
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </definition>

            <example>
                <p>
                    <m>\dfrac{dx}{dt}=kx</m> ( <m>k\in \mathbb{R}</m> ) is
                    linear and separable (autonomous).
                </p>
            </example>

            <example>
                <p>
                    <m>y'=(\cot x)y</m> is linear and separable.
                </p>
            </example>

            <example>
                <p>
                    <m>y'=y+x</m> is linear, but not separable.
                </p>
            </example>

            <example>
                <p>
                    <m>\dfrac{dy}{dt}=ky\left(1-\dfrac{y}{N}\right)</m> where
                    <m>k,N\in\mathbb{R}</m>, is nonlinear, separable (and
                    autonomous).
                </p>
            </example>

            <example>
                <p>
                    <m>y'=xy^{2}+\ln x</m> is neither linear nor separable.
                </p>
            </example>
        </subsection>
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- Subsection - Method of Integrating Factor -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <subsection>
            <title>Method of Integrating Factor</title>

            <p>
                This method is for solving a linear first-order differential
                equation
                <md>
                    y'+p(x)y=q(x).
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                It works by multiplying both sides by a suitable function
                <m>\mu(x)</m>, called an <term>integrating factor</term>,
                <md>
                    \mu(x)y'+p(x)\mu(x)y=\mu(x)q(x)
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                to make the left-hand side of the resulting equation
                recognizable as the derivative of a product:
                <md>
                    \left[\mu(x)y\right]'=\mu(x)y'+\mu'(x)y.
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                As we can see, the appropriate choice of <m>\mu(x)</m> is
                prescribed by the differential equation
                <md>
                    \mu'(x)=p(x)\mu(x).
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                Solving this DE by the method of separation of variables, we
                have
                <md>
                    \mu(x)=e^{\int p(x)\,dx}.
                </md>
            </p>

            <paragraphs>
                <title>How It Works</title>

                <p>
                    The method works as follows:
                </p>

                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Calculate the <em>integrating factor</em>
                                <md xml:id="eq-Integrating-factor" number="yes">
                                    \mu(x)=e^{\int p(x)\,dx}.
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Multiply both sides of the differential equation
                                by <m>\mu(x)</m>
                                <md>
                                    \mu(x)y'+p(x)\mu(x)y=\mu(x)q(x)
                                </md>
                            </p>

                            <p>
                                and recognize the left-hand side of the
                                resulting differential equation as the
                                derivative of a product to obtain the equation
                                <md>
                                    \left[\mu(x)y\right]'=\mu(x)q(x).
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Integrate both sides of the equation with
                                respect to <m>x</m> to obtain
                                <md>
                                    \mu(x)y=\int\mu(x)q(x)\,dx.
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Solve for <m>y</m> to obtain the general
                                solution of the original equation:
                                <md xml:id="eq-General-solution-using-integrating-factor" number="yes">
                                    y(x) =\dfrac{1}{\mu(x)}\int\mu(x)q(x)\,dx.
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>

                <warning>
                    <p>
                        You should <em>not</em> memorize formula
                        <xref ref="eq-General-solution-using-integrating-factor"/>.
                        Rather, you <em>should memorize</em> the formula for the
                        integrating factor <xref ref="eq-Integrating-factor"/>
                        and understand how to apply the integrating factor as in
                        <xref ref="example-Proper-linear"/> through
                        <xref ref="example-Linear-and-seperable"/>.
                    </p>
                </warning>
            </paragraphs>

            <note>
                <title>Some Notes about Linear Equations</title>

                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The general solution of a first-order linear
                                differential equation on an interval <m>I</m>
                                contains <em>all</em> of its particular
                                solutions, and thus, there are no singular ones.
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                It should be noted that the integrals we obtain
                                in the described method may be difficult, or
                                even impossible, to express in terms of
                                elementary functions.
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                In the formula for the integrating factor
                                <xref ref="eq-Integrating-factor"/>, we can
                                regard the integration constant in the integral
                                <m>\int p(x)\,dx</m> to be <m>0</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Given an initial value problem
                                <md xml:id="IVP1" number="yes">
                                    y'+p(x)y=q(x),\ y(x_{0})=y_{0},
                                </md>
                            </p>

                            <p>
                                where <m>x_{0}</m> is in an open interval
                                <m>I</m>, where the functions <m>p(x)</m> and
                                <m>q(x)</m> are continuous, we can find its
                                <em>unique</em> solution by first finding the
                                general solution using the method of integrating
                                factor and then finding the appropriate value of
                                the constant <m>c</m> by using the initial
                                condition.
                            </p>

                            <p>
                                We can also find the solution of initial value
                                problem <xref ref="IVP1"/> by adjusting formula
                                <xref ref="eq-General-solution-using-integrating-factor"/>
                                for the general solution of the differential
                                equation as follows:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow> \mu(x)\amp = e^{\int_{x_0}^x p(t)\,dt} </mrow>
                                    <mrow number="yes"> y\amp =\dfrac{1}{\mu(x)}\left[y_{0}+\int_{x_0}^{x} \mu(t)q(t)\,dt\right] </mrow>
                                    <mrow> \amp =e^{-\int_{x_0}^x p(t)\,dt}\left[y_{0}+\int_{x_0}^{x} e^{\int_{x_0}^x p(t)\,dt}q(t)\,dt\right]. </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </note>

            <example xml:id="example-Proper-linear">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Find the general solution of
                        <md>
                            y'+3y=2xe^{-3x}.
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        Since the equation is in the proper form, we first find
                        the integrating factor:
                        <md>
                            p(x) = 3, \text{ so }\mu(x) = e^{\int 3 \, dx}= e^{3x}.
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Multiplying both sides of the DE by <m>\mu(x)</m> gives
                        <md>
                            e^{3x}y'+3e^{3x}y=2x,
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        which we can recognize as
                        <md>
                            \dfrac{d}{dx}\left(e^{3x}y\right)=2x.
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p/>
                    <p>
                        Integrating both sides with respect to <m>x</m>, we
                        have:
                        <md>
                            <mrow> \int \dfrac{d}{dx}\left(e^{3x}y\right) \,dx\amp =\int 2x\,dx </mrow>
                            <mrow> e^{3x}y\amp = x^{2}+c\quad \text{($c\in \R$)}. </mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Solving for <m>y</m>, we obtain the general solution of
                        the DE
                        <md>
                            \boxed{y=e^{-3x}(x^2+c) \text{ ($c\in \R$)}.}
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        on <m>(-\infty,\infty)</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </example>

            <example>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Find a general solution of
                        <md>
                            (x^{2}+1)y' + 3xy = 6x.
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        First, we need to divide both sides of the equation by
                        <m>x^{2}+1</m> to get the equation in the proper form:
                        <md>
                            y' + \frac{3x}{x^{2}+1}y = \frac{6x}{x^{2}+1}.
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Find the integrating factor:
                        <md>
                            p(x) = \frac{3x}{x^{2}+1}, \text{ so }\mu(x) = e^{\int \frac{3x}{x^{2}+1}dx}= e^{\frac{3}{2}\ln(x^2+1)}=   (x^{2}+1)^{\frac{3}{2}}.
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Multiply both sides by <m>\mu(x)</m> and solve:
                        <md>
                            <mrow> (x^{2}+1)^{\frac{3}{2}}y' + \frac{3x}{x^{2}+1}(x^{2}+1)^{\frac{3}{2}}y\amp = \frac{6x}{x^{2}+1}(x^{2}+1)^{\frac{3}{2}} </mrow>
                            <mrow> (x^{2}+1)^{\frac{3}{2}}y' + 3(x^{2}+1)^{\frac{1}{2}}y\amp = 6x(x^{2}+1)^{\frac{1}{2}} </mrow>
                            <mrow> \frac{d}{dx}\left((x^{2}+1)^{\frac{3}{2}}y\right)\amp = 6x(x^{2}+1)^{\frac{1}{2}} </mrow>
                            <mrow> \int \frac{d}{dx}\left((x^{2}+1)^{\frac{3}{2}}y\right) dx\amp = \int 6x(x^{2}+1)^{\frac{1}{2}}dx </mrow>
                            <mrow> (x^{2}+1)^{\frac{3}{2}}y\amp = 2(x^{2} + 1)^{\frac{3}{2}}+ c </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp \hspace{-3mm}\boxed{y(x) = 2 + c(x^2+1)^{-\frac{3}{2}} \ (c \in \R).} </mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </example>

            <example>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Solve the initial value problem
                        <md>
                            y' - y = \frac{8}{11}e^{-\frac{x}{3}}, \ y(0) = -1.
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    First, find the general solution.
                                </p>

                                <p>
                                    <ul>
                                        <li>
                                            <p>
                                                Find the integrating factor:
                                            </p>

                                            <p>
                                                <md>
                                                    p(x) = -1, \text{ so }\mu(x) = e^{\int -1 dx}= e^{-x}.
                                                </md>
                                            </p>
                                        </li>

                                        <li>
                                            <p>
                                                Multiply both sides of the
                                                equation by
                                                <m>\mu(x) = e^{-x}</m> and
                                                solve.
                                                <md>
                                                    <mrow> e^{-x}y'-e^{-x}y\amp = \frac{8}{11}e^{-\frac{4x}{3}} </mrow>
                                                    <mrow> \frac{d}{dx}\left(e^{-x}y\right)\amp = \frac{8}{11}e^{-\frac{4x}{3}} </mrow>
                                                    <mrow> \int \frac{d}{dx}\left(e^{-x}y\right) dx\amp = \int \frac{8}{11}e^{-\frac{4x}{3}}dx </mrow>
                                                    <mrow> e^{-x}y\amp = -\frac{6}{11}e^{-\frac{4x}{3}}+ c </mrow>
                                                    <mrow> y\amp = -\frac{6}{11}e^{-\frac{x}{3}}+ ce^{x}. </mrow>
                                                </md>
                                            </p>
                                        </li>
                                    </ul>
                                </p>
                            </li>

                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Find <m>c</m>, using <m>y(0)=-1</m>:
                                </p>

                                <p>
                                    <md>
                                        -1 = -\frac{6}{11}+ c, \text{ so }c = -\frac{5}{11}.
                                    </md>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Therefore,
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <md>
                            \boxed{y(x) = -\frac{6}{11} e^{-\frac{x}{3}} - \frac{5}{11} e^x.}
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </example>

            <example xml:id="example-Linear-and-seperable">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Solve the initial value problem
                        <md xml:id="eq-Linear-and-seperable" number="yes">
                            \dfrac{dy}{dt}=\dfrac{2y+1}{t},\ y(1)=0.
                        </md>
                        Note this is equation is both <em>linear</em> and
                        <em>separable</em> (we solved it in the previous
                        section).
                        The equation <xref ref="eq-Linear-and-seperable"/> can
                        be separated as follows:
                        <md>
                            y'-\dfrac{2}{t}\;y=\dfrac{1}{t}
                        </md>
                        However, since the equation was initially presented in
                        the standard linear form, in this example we will solve
                        the original equation
                        <xref ref="eq-Linear-and-seperable"/> using an
                        integrating factor.
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    First, find the general solution.
                                </p>

                                <p>
                                    <ul>
                                        <li>
                                            <p>
                                                Since the equation is in the
                                                proper form, we first find the
                                                integrating factor:
                                            </p>

                                            <p>
                                                <md>
                                                    p(t) = -\frac{2}{t}\text{ so }\mu(t) = e^{-\int \frac{2}{t} \, dt}= e^{-2\ln |t|}= t^{-2}.
                                                </md>
                                            </p>
                                        </li>

                                        <li>
                                            <p>
                                                Multiplying both sides of the DE
                                                by <m>\mu(t)</m> gives
                                                <md>
                                                    t^{-2}y'-2t^{-3}y=t^{-3},
                                                </md>
                                            </p>

                                            <p>
                                                which we recognize as
                                                <md>
                                                    \left[t^{-2}y\right]'=t^{-3}.
                                                </md>
                                            </p>
                                        </li>

                                        <li>
                                            <p>
                                                Integrate both sides with
                                                respect to <m>t</m> to obtain:
                                                <md>
                                                    <mrow> \int\left[t^{-2}y\right]'\,dt\amp = \int t^{-3}\,dt  </mrow>
                                                    <mrow> t^{-2}y\amp = -\dfrac{1}{2}t^{-2}+c \quad (c\in \mathbb{R}). </mrow>
                                                </md>
                                            </p>
                                        </li>

                                        <li>
                                            <p>
                                                Solving for <m>y</m>, we find
                                                the general solution of the DE:
                                                <md>
                                                    y=ct^{2}-\dfrac{1}{2}\text{ ($c\in \R$)}
                                                </md>
                                            </p>

                                            <p>
                                                on each of the intervals
                                                <m>(-\infty,0)</m>,
                                                <m>(0,\infty)</m>.
                                            </p>
                                        </li>
                                    </ul>
                                </p>
                            </li>

                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    We determine <m>c</m> by plugging in the
                                    initial condition
                                    <md>
                                        0 = y(1) = c(1)^{2} - \dfrac{1}{2},
                                    </md>
                                </p>

                                <p>
                                    so <m>c = \dfrac{1}{2}</m>.
                                </p>

                                <p>
                                    Therefore, the solution of the IVP is
                                    <md>
                                        \boxed{y(t) =\dfrac{1}{2}t^2-\dfrac{1}{2},\  0&lt;t&lt;\infty.}
                                    </md>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        We can also solve this problem by using the definite
                        integral approach (see
                        <xref ref="eq-IVP-single-variable"/> ):
                        <md>
                            \mu(t)=\exp{\left(\int_{1}^t \left[-\dfrac{2}{x}\right]\,dx\right)}=\exp\left(-2\ln|t|\right)=t^{-2},\quad 0&lt;t&lt;\infty.
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        and the desired solution on <m>(0,\infty)</m> is
                        obtained from
                        <md>
                            <mrow> y\amp =\dfrac{1}{t^{-2}}\left[0+\int_{1}^{t} x^{-2}\dfrac{1}{x}\,dx \right]  </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp =t^{2}\left[\int_{1}^{t} x^{-3}\,dx \right] </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp =t^{2}\left[\left.-\dfrac{1}{2}x^{-2}\right|_{1}^{t} \right] </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp =t^{2}\left[\dfrac{1}{2}-\dfrac{1}{2}t^{-2}\right], </mrow>
                        </md>
                        so
                        <md>
                            \boxed{y(x) = \dfrac{1}{2}t^2-\dfrac{1}{2}, \  0 &lt; t &lt; \infty.}
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </example>
        </subsection>
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- Subsection - Mixing Problem with Variable Volume -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <subsection>
            <title>Application: Mixing Problem with Variable Volume</title>

            <example>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A tank initially contains 1,000 gal of water in which is
                        dissolved 20 lb of salt.
                        A valve is opened and water containing 0.25 lb of salt
                        per gallon flows into the tank at a rate of 4 gal/min.
                        Assume that the mixture is kept uniform and drains from
                        the tank at a rate of 5 gal/min.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Set up an initial value problem describing
                                    how the amount of salt in the tank changes
                                    over time.
                                </p>
                            </li>

                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    At what time is the tank empty?
                                </p>
                            </li>

                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    How much salt does the tank contain at any
                                    time <m>t</m> before the tank is empty?
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Recall the model for a mixing problem
                    </p>

                    <blockquote>
                        <p>
                            rate of change in amount of solute = solute inflow
                            rate - solute outflow rate
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            (i.e., <m>y' = \text{rate in}- \text{rate out}</m>
                            ).
                        </p>
                    </blockquote>

                    <p>
                        Recall the following.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Each solute inflow rate is found by multiplying the rate
                        at which fluid flows into the container by the
                        concentration of solute:
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <md>
                            \text{inflow rate}= \text{(rate of fluid inflow)}\cdot \text{(concentration of solute)}.
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Each solute outflow rate is found by multiplying the
                        rate at which fluid flows out of the container by the
                        concentration of solute in the container:
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <md>
                            \text{outflow rate}=   \left(\text{rate of fluid outflow}\right) \cdot \left(\frac{\text{amount of solute in container}}{\text{volume of solution in container}}\right).
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        Proceed as follows:
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    For our problem, since the rate of fluid
                                    flowing into the tank is not equal to the
                                    rate flowing out of the tank, the volume of
                                    solution at any time <m>t</m> is not the
                                    same as the initial volume, 1000.
                                    Let <m>v(t) =</m> volume of solution in the
                                    tank at time <m>t</m>.
                                    The volume at any time <m>t</m> is
                                    determined by
                                </p>

                                <p>
                                    <md>
                                        \text{volume}= \text{initial volume}+ (\text{fluid inflow rate})t - (\text{fluid outflow rate})t.
                                    </md>
                                </p>

                                <p>
                                    Therefore,
                                    <md>
                                        <mrow> v(t)\amp = 1000 + 4t - 5t = 1000 - t </mrow>
                                        <mrow> \text{rate in}\amp = 4 \, \frac{\text{gal}}{\text{min}}\cdot 0.25 \, \frac{\text{lb}}{\text{gal}}=   1 \, \frac{\text{lb}}{\text{min}} </mrow>
                                        <mrow> \text{rate out}\amp = 5 \, \frac{\text{gal}}{\text{min}}\cdot \frac{y}{1000 - t}\, \frac{\text{lb}}{\text{gal}}= \frac{5y}{1000-t}\, \frac{\text{lb}}{\text{min}} </mrow>
                                    </md>
                                </p>

                                <p>
                                    So, we have
                                    <md>
                                        y' = 1 - \frac{5y}{1000-t}.
                                    </md>
                                </p>

                                <p>
                                    Rewriting in the form for a linear equation,
                                    we obtain
                                    <md>
                                        y' + \frac{5}{1000-t}y = 1, \ y(0) = 20.
                                    </md>
                                </p>
                            </li>

                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    To determine the time at which the tank is
                                    empty, we use
                                    <md>
                                        1000 - t = 0, \text{ or }t = 1000 \text{ min}.
                                    </md>
                                </p>
                            </li>

                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Find the integrating factor:
                                    <md>
                                        p(t) = \frac{5}{1000-t}\text{ so }\mu(t) = e^{\int \frac{5}{1000-t} \, dt}= (1000-t)^{-5}
                                    </md>.
                                </p>

                                <p>
                                    Multiply by <m>\mu(t)</m>:
                                    <md>
                                        <mrow> (1000-t)^{-5}y' + 5(1000-t)^{-6}y\amp = (1000-t)^{-5} </mrow>
                                        <mrow> \int \frac{d}{dt}\left((1000-t)^{-5}y\right) \, dt\amp = \int (1000-t)^{-5}\, dt </mrow>
                                        <mrow> (1000-t)^{-5}y\amp = \frac{1}{4}(1000-t)^{-4}+c </mrow>
                                        <mrow> y\amp = \frac{1}{4}(1000-t) + c(1000-t)^{5} </mrow>
                                    </md>
                                </p>

                                <p>
                                    Find <m>c</m>: Since y(0) = 20,
                                    <md>
                                        20 = 250 + c, \text{ so }c = -\frac{230}{1000^{5}}
                                    </md>.
                                </p>

                                <p>
                                    So, we have that for
                                    <m>0 \le t \le 1000</m>,
                                    <md>
                                        \boxed{y(t) = \frac{1}{4}(1000-t) - \frac{230}{1000^{5}}(1000-t)^5 \text{ kg}.}
                                    </md>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </example>
        </subsection>
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- Subsection - Excercises for Linear Equations -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <subsection>
            <title>Exercises for Section <xref ref="linear"/></title>

            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            What is the integrating factor for the equation
                            <m>y'-2xy=8x</m>?
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Consider the problem
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            <md>
                                \cos (x) y' = -\sin (x) y.
                            </md>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Is the equation separable?
                                        Why?
                                    </p>
                                </li>

                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Is the equation linear?
                                        Why?
                                    </p>
                                </li>

                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Find a general solution.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Give an example of an equation that is both
                            separable and linear.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>

            <p>
                Find a general solution for each of the following equations.
            </p>

            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle y' - 2xy = 8x</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle xy' + 2y = x^{4}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle y' = 2y - x^{2}y + 1</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle e^{x} (y' + y) = e^{-x}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle (x^{2} + 1)y' = x^{2} + 2xy + 1</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle y' = y\cos(x) + 2\cos(x)</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>

            <p>
                Solve the following initial value problems.
            </p>

            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle y' + 2xy = 6x, \ y(0) = 0</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle (x^{2} + 1) y' + 2xy = e^{2x}, \ y(0) = -1</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle 2yy' = 6xy^{2} + 3xy, \ y(0) = -1</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle 2xy' - 4x^{2}y = 12x^{-2}e^{x^2}, \ y(1) = 0</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>

            <p>
                Solve the following mixing problems.
            </p>

            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            A 100 gallon tank initially contains 50 gal of brine
                            containing 5 pounds of salt.
                            Brine containing 1 pound of salt per gallon enters
                            the tank at the rate of 4 gal/s, and the well-mixed
                            brine in the tank flows out at the rate of 3 gal/s.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        How much salt will the tank contain at
                                        the time when the tank is full of brine?
                                    </p>
                                </li>

                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        If the tank had an infinite capacity,
                                        what is the maximum amount of salt that
                                        it could contain?
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            A 50 L tank initially contains 40 L of brine in
                            which is dissolved 1 kg of salt.
                            Pure water enters the tank at the rate of 3 L/s, and
                            the well-mixed solution in the tank flows out at the
                            rate of 4 L/s.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        How long before the tank is empty?
                                    </p>
                                </li>

                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        How much salt will be in the solution in
                                        the tank at any time <m>t</m> before the
                                        tank is empty?
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </subsection>
    </section>
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- Section - Substitution Method -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <!-- ===================================================== -->
    <section xml:id="sec-subs">
        <title>Substitution Method</title>

        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- Subsection - Substitution Method -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <subsection>
            <title>General Idea</title>

            <p>
                The general idea of the <term>Substitution Method</term> for a
                first order differential of the form
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    \dfrac{dy}{dx}= f(x, y)
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                is to
            </p>

            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            introduce a new function
                            <md xml:id="subst1" number="yes">
                                v = g(x,y),
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            differentiate by the <em>Chain Rule</em>
                            (considering that <m>y = y(x)</m> )
                            <md xml:id="subst2" number="yes">
                                \dfrac{dv}{dx}= \dfrac{\partial g}{\partial x}(x, y) + \dfrac{\partial g}{\partial y}(x, y)\dfrac{dy}{dx},
                            </md>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            and
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            solve <xref ref="subst2"/> <m>y'</m> and
                            <xref ref="subst1"/> for <m>y</m> (if necessary) and
                            substitute into the original DE to obtain a new
                            first-order DE for <m>v</m> that would belong to one
                            of the two classes of DE's that we know how to solve
                            ( <em>separable</em> or <em>linear</em> );
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            solve the obtained DE for <m>v</m>; and
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            substitute <m>v=g(x,y)</m> back into the result to
                            obtain an <em>implicit solution</em> of the original
                            DE for <m>y</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>

            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            A "good" substitution <m>v=g(x, y)</m> simplifies
                            the DE, turning into one we can solve.
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Obtaining an <em>explicit solution</em> for <m>y</m>
                            may be possible but is not always practical.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>

            <example>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Find a general solution of
                        <md>
                            (2x\sin y\cos y)y'=4x^{2}+\sin^{2}y.
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </statement>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        Observe that, assuming <m>y</m> to be a function of
                        <m>x</m>, <m>y=y(x)</m>, by the chain rule, we have:
                        <md>
                            \dfrac{d}{dx}(\sin^{2} y)=2\sin y\cos y y'.
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Hence via the substitution
                        <md>
                            v=\sin^{2} y,\text{ so }v'=2\sin y\cos y y',
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        the DE is transformed into
                        <md>
                            xv'=4x^{2}+v,
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        which we write in standard form is
                        <md>
                            v'-\dfrac{1}{x}v=4x.
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        The latter differential equation is linear, so we may
                        solve it using the method of integrating factor.
                        The integrating factor is
                        <md>
                            \mu(x)=e^{-\int\frac{1}{x}\,dx}=e^{-\ln|x|}=\dfrac{1}{x}\quad \text{(the absolute value can be omitted)}.
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Multiplying both sides by <m>\mu(x)=\dfrac{1}{x}</m> and
                        recognizing the left-hand side as the derivative of a
                        product, we have:
                        <md>
                            \left(\dfrac{1}{x}v\right)'=4.
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Integrating both sides with respect to <m>x</m> gives
                        <md>
                            \dfrac{1}{x}v=\int 4\,dx=4x+c\quad (c\in \mathbb{R}).
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Solving for <m>v</m>, we obtain
                        <md>
                            v=4x^{2}+cx\quad (c\in \mathbb{R})
                        </md>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        and substituting back, we obtain an implicit general
                        solution of the original equation,
                        <md>
                            \boxed{\sin^2 y=4x^2+cx \text{ where } (c\in\mathbb{R}).}
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </example>
        </subsection>
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- Subsection - Homogenous Equations -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <!-- ===================================================== -->
        <subsection>
            <title>Homogeneous Differential Equations</title>

            <paragraphs>
                <title>
                    Motivating Example: Solar Collector <xref ref="Zill"/>
                </title>

                <p>
                    If we assume that when the curve <m>C</m> shown below is
                    revolved about the <m>x</m>-axis, it produces a surface of
                    revolution having the property that all light rays <m>L</m>
                    parallel to the <m>x</m>-axis, upon striking the surface,
                    are reflected to one point <m>O</m>, which we label the
                    origin.
                </p>

                <image source="solarCollector.png" width="80%">
                    <description>
                        <p>
                            Ray from the origin reflects parallel to
                            <m>x</m>-axis when ray hits the curve.
                        </p>
                    </description>
                </image>

                <p>
                    Using the fact that the angle of incidence is equal to the
                    angle of reflection, we can determine a differential
                    equation that describes the shape of the curve <m>C</m>.
                    This type of curve is important in applications, such as the
                    construction of telescopes and satellite antennas,
                    automobile headlights, and solar collectors.
                    From geometry, we can see that the angle between the
                    reflected line and the <m>x</m>-axis, denoted <m>\phi</m>,
                    and the angle between <m>L</m> and <m>C</m> at the point of
                    incidence, denoted <m>\theta</m> are related by
                    <m>\phi = 2\theta</m>.
                    Using this, we obtain the differential equation
                </p>

                <p>
                    <md>
                        \frac{dy}{dx}= \frac{-x + \sqrt{x^{2} + y^{2}}}{y}.
                    </md>
                    This equation is nonlinear and homogeneous, where
                    homogeneous will be defined below.
                    The solution of this problem requires a bit more work than
                    the examples which we will do, because it results in a
                    complicated integral.
                    A general solution is
                </p>

                <p>
                    <md>
                        y^{2} = c(c-2x),
                    </md>
                </p>

                <p>
                    which is a parabola that is symmetric with respect to the
                    <m>x</m>-axis.
                    Try to see if you can obtain this solution.
                </p>

                <note>
                    <p>
                        This problem may also be solved by a different type of
                        substitution, namely, <m>u = x^{2} + y^{2}</m>.
                        We will discuss such substitutions a bit later.
                    </p>
                </note>

                <definition xml:id="def-First-order-homogeneous">
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            First-Order Homogeneous Differential Equations
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            A
                            <term>first-order homogeneous differential equation</term>
                            is a first-order differential equation that can be
                            written as
                            <md xml:id="eq-First-order-homogeneous" number="yes">
                                \frac{dy}{dx}= F\left(\frac{y}{x}\right).
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                </definition>

                <p>
                    To solve differential equation <xref ref="eq-First-order-homogeneous"/>, make
                    the substitution
                    <md>
                        v= \frac{y}{x}
                    </md>.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Therefore,
                    <md>
                        y= vx\quad \text{and}\quad\frac{dy}{dx}= x \frac{dv}{dx}+ v
                    </md>.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Substituting into <xref ref="eq-First-order-homogeneous"/> gives
                    <md>
                        x \frac{dv}{dx}+ v = F(v) \text{ so }x \frac{dv}{dx}= F(v) - v
                    </md>,
                    which is a separable equation.
                </p>

                <example>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Find a general solution of
                            <md>
                                x^{3}y'=x^{2}y-y^{3}.
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </statement>

                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            Dividing both sides by <m>x^{3}</m>, we see that we
                            obtain:
                            <md>
                                y'=\dfrac{y}{x}-\left(\dfrac{y}{x}\right)^{3}.
                            </md>
                            Therefore, the DE is homogeneous.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            Substituting
                            <md>
                                v=\dfrac{y}{x},\text{ so }y=xv \text{ and }y'=v+xv',
                            </md>
                            we obtain the separable DE
                            <md>
                                v+xv'=v-v^{3}.
                            </md>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            The equilibrium solution is <m>v=0</m>.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            Separating the variables and integrating, we have:
                            <md>
                                <mrow> -\int v^{-3}\,dv\amp =\int \dfrac{1}{x}\,dx </mrow>
                                <mrow> \frac{1}{2}v^{-2}\amp = \ln|x|+c \quad \text{($c\in \R$)} </mrow>
                            </md>.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            (Note that the singular equilibrium solution
                            <m>v=0</m> is not included.)
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            Multiplying by 2 and substituting back, we obtain an
                            implicit general solution of the initial problem
                            <md>
                                \boxed{\dfrac{x^2}{y^2}=2\ln|x|+c \text{ ($c\in \R$)}.}
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </example>

                <note>
                    <p>
                        In the previous example:
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    The singular equilibrium solution <m>y=0</m>
                                    is not included.
                                </p>
                            </li>

                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Since the DE is nonlinear, singular
                                    solutions were to be expected.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </note>

                <example>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Solve the initial value problem
                            <md>
                                xyy' = 2y^{2} + 4x^{2}, \ y(2) = 4.
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </statement>

                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            Divide by <m>xy</m> to get the equation in standard
                            form:
                            <md>
                                y' = 2\frac{y}{x}+ 4 \frac{x}{y}.
                            </md>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            This is a homogeneous equation, so let
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            <md>
                                v = \frac{y}{x},\\ \text{ and so }y = vx \text{ and }y' = xv' + v.
                            </md>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            Plugging into our DE gives
                            <md>
                                <mrow> xv'+v\amp = 2v+\frac{4}{v} </mrow>
                                <mrow> xv'\amp = v + \frac{4}{v} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \frac{v^{2}+4}{v} </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            So, we have
                            <md>
                                x\frac{dv}{dx}= \frac{v^{2}+4}{v}.
                            </md>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            Then
                            <md>
                                \int \frac{v}{v^{2}+4}dv= \int \frac{1}{x}dx
                            </md>.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            Integrating by using the substitution
                            <m>u = v^{2} + 4</m> for the left-hand integral
                            gives
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \frac{1}{2}\ln(v^{2}+4)\amp = \ln|x| + c_{1} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \ln(v^{2} + 4)\amp = 2 \ln|x| + c_{2} </mrow>
                                <mrow> e^{\ln(v^2+4)}\amp = e^{2\ln|x| + c_2} </mrow>
                                <mrow> (v^{2}+4)\amp = cx^{2} </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            Substituting back in <m>\displaystyle v = \frac{y}{x}</m>
                            gives
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \left(\frac{y}{x}\right)^{2} + 4\amp = cx^{2}, \amp\text{or}y^{2} + 4x^{2}\amp = cx^{4}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            Find <m>c</m>: Since <m>y(2) = 4</m>, we have
                            <m>4^{2} + 4(2)^{2} = c(2)^{4}</m>, so <m>c = 2</m>.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            So we obtain the unique solution
                            <md>
                                \boxed{y^2 + 4x^2 = 2x^4.}
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </example>
            </paragraphs>
        </subsection>
    </section>
</chapter>